GOOD FRIDAY

INVITATORY:
Come, let us worship Christ, the Son of God, who redeemed us with his blood.

VIGILS
PSALMODY
Ps 2 - Ps 21 - Ps 37

LAUDS
READING:    Is 52:13-15    See, my servant shall prosper, he shall be raised high and greatly exalted. Even as many were amazed at him— so marred were his features, beyond that of mortals his appearance, beyond that of human beings— So shall he startle many nations, kings shall stand speechless; for those who have not been told shall see, those who have not heard shall ponder it.

BENEDICTUS:	Over his head they hung their accusation: Jesus of Nazareth, King of the Jews.

PRAYER:	O God, who by the Passion of Christ your Son, our Lord, abolished the death inherited from ancient sin by every succeeding generation, grant that just as, being conformed to him, we have borne by the law of nature the image of the man of earth, so by the sanctification of grace we may bear the image of the Man of heaven. Through Christ our Lord.

SEXT
PSALMODY
Ps 35 - Ps 53 - Ps 87

READING:    Is 53:4-5    Yet it was our pain that he bore, our sufferings he endured. We thought of him as stricken, struck down by God and afflicted, but he was pierced for our sins, crushed for our iniquity. He bore the punishment that makes us whole, by his wounds we were healed.
Lord, remember me.
- When you come into your kingdom.

VESPERS
HYMN p. ?
PSALMODY
Ps 115 - Ps 141 - Ps 142 - NT 5

READING:    1 Pet 2:21-24    For to this you have been called, because Christ also suffered* for you, leaving you an example that you should follow in his footsteps. “He committed no sin, and no deceit was found in his mouth.” When he was insulted, he returned no insult; when he suffered, he did not threaten; instead, he handed himself over to the one who judges justly. He himself bore our sins in his body upon the cross, so that, free from sin, we might live for righteousness. By his wounds you have been healed.

MAGNIFICAT:	When we were his enemies , God reconciled us to himself by the death of his Son.

Compline from Sunday, after Second Vespers

